//@ compile-fail
//@ error-contains: is opaque

// The two things `any` still lets through. Both are open, both are recorded here, and
// this file is deliberately absent from expected-pass.txt until they close.
//
// 1. THE READ (`thief::read`). An opaque widens to `any` and a structural `is`/`as`
//    probes it. The checker accepts this because the type in play is `any` --
//    module-blind by construction. It does NOT leak the contents: a boxed value carries
//    a *nominal* runtime tag, so `is { code: i64 }` compares Secret's tag against the
//    structural shape's, they differ, and the branch is dead (verified 2026-07-20, dead
//    even inside `vault`). So this is an incoherence -- a statically-legal,
//    could-be-true test that is runtime-always-false -- not a disclosure.
//
// 2. THE FORGE (`thief::forge`). A structural value widens to `any` and casts to the
//    nominal, and the runtime cast reads bytes without checking the tag, so it produces
//    a working `Secret` from `{ code: 99 }`. This one is a real hole.
//
//    It cannot be closed statically without breaking legitimate code, and that is the
//    point worth recording: `any` can genuinely hold an opaque -- widening into `any` is
//    a legal flow -- so a cast out of `any` is indistinguishable from the pinned
//    erased-recovery idiom `(li: any) as List[i64]`
//    (types/list_literal_erased_into_any_recovered.neon). A static rule strict enough to
//    stop the forge also rejects that. Verified by trying it: the strict rule broke five
//    corpus files.
//
//    The fix is at run time, where the two ARE distinguishable: `as` from `any` to a
//    concrete target should compare the box tag against the target's and trap on
//    mismatch. Honest recovery passes, forgery traps. That is a general soundness fix --
//    unguarded `as`-from-`any` is unchecked for every type, not just opaque ones -- and
//    is worth doing with the bare-name identity fix (TODO #1), since same-name records
//    share a tag. See docs/design/opacity.md.
//
// The direct, non-`any` spellings of both are closed and pinned:
// opaque_no_structural_cast.neon and opaque_no_anonymous_forgery.neon.

use std::io;

internal mod vault {
    opaque record Secret { code: i64 }
    fn seal(n: i64) -> Secret { Secret { code: n } }
    fn value(s: Secret) -> i64 { s.code }
}

internal mod thief {
    // 1. The read: accepted by the checker, dead at run time.
    fn read(s: vault::Secret) -> i64 {
        let a: any = s;
        if a is { code: i64 } {
            (a as { code: i64 }).code
        } else {
            0
        }
    }

    // 2. The forge: accepted by the checker, and it WORKS at run time.
    fn forge() -> vault::Secret {
        let a: any = { code: 99 };
        a as vault::Secret
    }
}

fn main() {
    io::println(to_string(thief::read(vault::seal(1234))));
    io::println(to_string(vault::value(thief::forge())));
}
